🚀 Day 03 — Linux File Management Commands

File management is a daily task in DevOps.
Today we will learn how to create, copy, move, delete, and read files in Linux.

📌 Why File Management is Important?

DevOps Engineers regularly:

📂 Manage configuration files
📜 Read logs
🛠️ Edit deployment scripts
🧹 Remove unused files
📦 Organize project directories
📄 1. cp — Copy Files & Directories
📌 Definition

cp is used to copy files and directories.

🛠️ Syntax
cp source destination
✅ Example 1 — Copy File
cp notes.txt backup.txt

📖 Creates a copy of notes.txt named backup.txt.

✅ Example 2 — Copy Directory
cp -r project backup-project

📂 -r means recursive copy.

🚚 2. mv — Move or Rename Files
📌 Definition

mv is used to:

Move files/directories
Rename files/directories
🛠️ Syntax
mv old_name new_name
✅ Example 1 — Rename File
mv notes.txt linux-notes.txt
✅ Example 2 — Move File
mv linux-notes.txt /home/ubuntu/Documents

📂 Moves file to another directory.

❌ 3. rm — Remove Files & Directories
📌 Definition

rm deletes files and directories.

⚠️ Deleted files usually cannot be recovered.

🛠️ Syntax
rm filename
✅ Example 1 — Delete File
rm notes.txt
✅ Example 2 — Delete Directory
rm -r project

📂 -r removes directory recursively.

⚠️ Dangerous Command
rm -rf
Option	Meaning
-r	Recursive delete
-f	Force delete

🚨 Use carefully in production servers.

📖 4. cat — Display File Content
📌 Definition

cat displays file content inside terminal.

🛠️ Syntax
cat filename
✅ Example
cat notes.txt

Output:

Linux is important for DevOps.
✍️ 5. nano — Terminal Text Editor
📌 Definition

nano is a simple command-line text editor.

Used to:

Edit configuration files
Write scripts
Modify logs
🛠️ Syntax
nano filename
✅ Example
nano notes.txt
💾 Save & Exit in Nano
Shortcut	Action
CTRL + O	Save
CTRL + X	Exit
🔝 6. head — View Beginning of File
📌 Definition

Displays first 10 lines of a file.

🛠️ Syntax
head filename
✅ Example
head logs.txt
🔻 7. tail — View End of File
📌 Definition

Displays last 10 lines of a file.

Very useful for monitoring logs.

🛠️ Syntax
tail filename
✅ Example
tail logs.txt
🔥 Real DevOps Command
Live Log Monitoring
tail -f application.log

📡 Shows live log updates in real-time.

Used heavily in:

Kubernetes
Docker
Production servers

🧪 Hands-On Practice

Run these commands step-by-step:

mkdir file-management
cd file-management

touch notes.txt
nano notes.txt

cat notes.txt

cp notes.txt backup.txt

mv backup.txt devops.txt

ls -l

rm devops.txt

📂 Real DevOps Scenario
Create Deployment Script
touch deploy.sh
Edit Script
nano deploy.sh

Add:

echo "Deployment Started"
Make Script Executable
chmod +x deploy.sh
Run Script
./deploy.sh

Output:

Deployment Started
🎯 Important Commands Summary
Command	Purpose
cp	Copy files/directories
mv	Move or rename
rm	Delete files
cat	View file content
nano	Edit files
head	View first lines
tail	View last lines

💡 Key Learnings

✅ Linux file management is essential for DevOps
✅ cp creates backups
✅ mv organizes files
✅ rm deletes unwanted data
✅ nano edits files directly from terminal
✅ tail -f is important for live log monitoring
